ety_name>duranii</variety_name><variety_authority>Jepson</variety_authority></TaxonIdentification><description>Basal leaves: blade obovate to spatulate, apex obtuse or rounded. Cauline leaves: blade broadly oblong to ovate or suborbicular, apex rounded to obtuse. Fruits 2.5–6(–7) mm wide; stigma subentire to strongly 2-lobed. 2n = 28, 56.</description><phenology>apr</phenology><phenology>spring</phenology><phenology>may</phenology><phenology>jun</phenology><phenology>summer</phenology><phenology>jul</phenology><habitat>dry stony slopes</habitat><habitat>sandy draws</habitat><habitat>limestone ledges</habitat><habitat>gravelly knolls</habitat><habitat>pinyon-juniper woodlands</habitat><habitat>sagebrush</habitat><habitat>open pine forests</habitat><elevation>500–3100 m;</elevation><us_distribution>Ariz.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Calif.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Colo.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Idaho</us_distribution><us_distribution>Nev.</us_distribution><us_distribution>N.Mex.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Oreg.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Utah</us_distribution><us_distribution>Wyo.</us_distribution><discussion>Some authors (e.g., R. E. Buck et al. 1993; R. C. Rollins 1993; N. H. Holmgren 2005b) reported var. cordatus (as Streptanthus cordatus) to have 2n = 24. That count must be an error, one that has been perpetuated in the literature since it was first reported in 1939 (S. I. Warwick and I. A. Al-Shehbaz 2006).</discussion></treatment>
